{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509966","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509966"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:22:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:22:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11467"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11467","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11467"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.41,0.27,0.05,0.17,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4099"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110692"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4099","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4099"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11467"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92940"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"28"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"337"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4979"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11639"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4939"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6522"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8666"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12733"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41714"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43229"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110692"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EYou are a general medical registrar reviewing your 82-year-old patient who is admitted under your care with end-stage heart failure. He is experiencing ongoing breathlessness at rest despite maximal tolerated medical therapy, including furosemide 120 mg twice daily. Previous trials of thiazide diuretics and intravenous furosemide have been unsuccessful and complicated by worsening renal function. He has a history of chronic kidney disease, with his most recent creatinine clearance being 25 mL/min. After discussion with him and his family, the plan is to focus on comfort measures and symptom management. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis current medications are furosemide 120 mg twice daily, perindopril 5 mg in the morning, bisoprolol 10 mg in the morning, spironolactone 25 mg in the morning, atorvastatin 20 mg daily, and aspirin 150 mg daily.\u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EOn examination, he appears tachypnoeic at rest. His oxygen saturation is 97% on room air. He has bi-basal crackles on chest auscultation, dual heart sounds with no murmurs, and pitting oedema to his knees.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management of his dyspnoea?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral morphine PRN","Oral hydromorphone PRN","Oral lorazepam PRN","Home oxygen therapy","Subcutaneous fentanyl"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EEnd-stage heart failure is characterised by severe symptoms at rest despite maximal medical therapy. When standard treatments are no longer effective, the focus shifts to palliative care and symptom control. Dyspnoea is a common and distressing symptom in this context.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral morphine PRN\u003C/strong\u003E is generally considered first-line for the management of refractory dyspnoea in palliative care, as it reduces the perception of breathlessness by acting on central opioid receptors. However, in people with significant renal impairment, morphine\u0027s active metabolites can accumulate, increasing the risk of adverse effects such as myoclonus and neurotoxicity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral hydromorphone PRN\u003C/strong\u003E is preferred in this scenario because it produces fewer active metabolites and is safer in the context of reduced renal function. It is an effective alternative to morphine for managing dyspnoea in people with chronic kidney disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral lorazepam PRN\u003C/strong\u003E may be used as an adjunct to opioids to address anxiety associated with breathlessness, but there is insufficient evidence to support its use as monotherapy for dyspnoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHome oxygen therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated for the relief of breathlessness in people with normal oxygen saturation, as in this case. Oxygen may be considered if there is hypoxaemia, but it does not improve the sensation of breathlessness in people who are not hypoxic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubcutaneous fentanyl\u003C/strong\u003E is an option for symptom control in people with severe renal impairment or when oral administration is not possible. However, oral administration is less invasive and preferred if the person can swallow and absorb medications, as in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Low-dose opioids are first-line pharmacological therapy for refractory dyspnoea in end-stage heart failure in a palliative setting.","Morphine is generally first-line, but alternatives such as hydromorphone are preferred in significant renal impairment due to reduced risk of metabolite accumulation.","Oxygen therapy is not indicated for breathlessness in people with normal oxygen saturation."],"references":["LeMond L, Goodlin SJ. Management of Heart Failure in Patients Nearing the End of Life-There is So Much More To Do. Card Fail Rev. 2015 Apr;1(1):31-34. doi: 10.15420/cfr.2015.01.01.31. PMID: 28785428; PMCID: PMC5490973.","Lowey SE. Palliative Care in the Management of Patients with Advanced Heart Failure. Adv Exp Med Biol. 2018;1067:295-311."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92940"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11467"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92940"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-03T11:28:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-03T11:28:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4099"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110692"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"28","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/28"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc95","name":"Palliative Care","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/78"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level III","synonyms":null,"description":"Apply, analyze, evaluate, and create (implementing, organizing, and critiquing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"